1
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:37,600
Hello.

2
00:01:37,600 --> 00:01:39,800
MISTY:
When I think about that time...

3
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:43,800
...it's not the heat,
the dust, the nuns...

4
00:01:44,500 --> 00:01:46,900
...or even the boys I remember...

5
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,300
...so much as a sense of anticipation.

6
00:01:51,600 --> 00:01:56,300
The constant belief
that somehow I'd be saved.

7
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:27,400
I wouldn't say we had it bad...

8
00:02:27,700 --> 00:02:30,900
...since it was all most of us knew.

9
00:02:31,700 --> 00:02:34,700
It was only there was something
just out of reach...

10
00:02:34,900 --> 00:02:37,000
...and we might never catch up.

11
00:02:48,000 --> 00:02:49,400
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

12
00:03:03,800 --> 00:03:06,400
Lights out, boys.

13
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:15,400
May you be blessed
and sleep with God's benevolent grace.

14
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:18,100
BO YS:
Amen.

15
00:03:29,200 --> 00:03:31,600
[BO YS WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

16
00:03:33,700 --> 00:03:35,800
MAPS:
Sparks.

17
00:03:46,300 --> 00:03:48,500
[WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

18
00:04:02,800 --> 00:04:04,500
[BO Y COUGHS]

19
00:04:04,700 --> 00:04:05,800
[DOOR CLOSES]

20
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:07,900
BO Y:
Someone's coming.

21
00:04:45,800 --> 00:04:50,100
MISTY: I don't remember who wrote
"I love a sunburnt country"...

22
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:53,400
...but I'd bet money
they never lived out here.

23
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:59,400
Just look at it.
It's the definition of desolate.

24
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:03,000
This is where I lived
most of my young years.

25
00:05:03,200 --> 00:05:05,900
This is where I lived until,
you could say...

26
00:05:06,100 --> 00:05:08,100
...I was rescued by a dream.

27
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:20,600
These were my best friends.

28
00:05:20,700 --> 00:05:25,300
Spark, Spit and Maps.

29
00:05:25,500 --> 00:05:29,800
My real name's Vernon,
but they call me Misty.

30
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:32,300
No reason to go into that right now.

31
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:33,800
[BEATRICE COUGHS]

32
00:05:33,900 --> 00:05:36,700
Today's the first of December...

33
00:05:36,900 --> 00:05:40,400
...the December boys
please come forward.

34
00:05:41,300 --> 00:05:44,400
MISTY: They say the best place to start
is the beginning.

35
00:05:44,600 --> 00:05:48,500
So, first off, you better know
we were all orphans.

36
00:05:50,800 --> 00:05:53,100
BEATRICE: Happy birthday.
- Thanks, Sister.

37
00:05:53,200 --> 00:05:55,400
Thanks, Sister.

38
00:05:58,200 --> 00:05:59,200
Thank you.

39
00:05:59,400 --> 00:06:00,900
BEATRICE:
Everybody ready?

40
00:06:01,100 --> 00:06:02,600
[BEATRICE CLEARS THRO AT]

41
00:06:02,900 --> 00:06:07,400
[BEATRICE AND BO YS SINGING
"FOR THEY ARE JOLLY GOOD FELLOWS"]

42
00:06:12,900 --> 00:06:14,600
SPIT:
It's about the smokes.

43
00:06:14,800 --> 00:06:17,000
I told you
she looks under the mattress.

44
00:06:17,100 --> 00:06:20,900
- I didn't put them there.
MISTY: It's about mooning Willie.

45
00:06:36,700 --> 00:06:38,600
REVEREND MOTHER:
Enter.

46
00:06:47,300 --> 00:06:49,500
Come in, boys.

47
00:06:53,700 --> 00:06:55,400
Father Scully...

48
00:06:55,600 --> 00:06:59,800
...this is James, Donald,
Bruce and Vernon.

49
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:04,800
Better known as Maps,
Spark, Spit and Misty.

50
00:07:05,200 --> 00:07:06,700
They're our December boys.

51
00:07:06,900 --> 00:07:08,200
SCULLY:
Oh.

52
00:07:08,900 --> 00:07:11,900
- Happy birthday.
BO YS: Thank you, Father.

53
00:07:12,200 --> 00:07:15,400
We have a little surprise for you.

54
00:07:15,800 --> 00:07:18,700
Oh, it's a pleasant surprise.

55
00:07:18,900 --> 00:07:21,900
A benefactor has left
St. Gregory's a little money...

56
00:07:22,100 --> 00:07:26,000
...and I've decided to send everyone
on a holiday.

57
00:07:26,500 --> 00:07:28,800
As this is your birthday month...

58
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,400
...I felt it fitting
you should be the first to go.

59
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:32,900
We're going on a holiday?

60
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:36,300
SCULLY: You'll be staying
with Mr. and Mrs. McAnsh.

61
00:07:36,500 --> 00:07:38,200
They're great friends
of the Church.

62
00:07:38,900 --> 00:07:40,600
REVEREND MOTHER:
It's a town called...

63
00:07:40,800 --> 00:07:44,000
...Lady Star Cove.

64
00:07:44,800 --> 00:07:46,200
It's a special place...

65
00:07:47,600 --> 00:07:50,100
...on the sea.

66
00:07:52,700 --> 00:07:55,200
On the sea?

67
00:07:58,900 --> 00:08:01,000
Yes.

68
00:08:01,100 --> 00:08:06,600
It could be
that Our Lady interceded for you.

69
00:08:08,800 --> 00:08:12,300
MISTY: I had this spiritual antenna
other people didn't have.

70
00:08:13,900 --> 00:08:17,300
That's why I could see things
no one else could.

71
00:08:17,600 --> 00:08:20,400
When I looked at Our Lady, I knew.

72
00:08:20,600 --> 00:08:25,500
I knew she'd chosen me
for a special mission.

73
00:08:42,900 --> 00:08:44,300
Whoa.

74
00:08:44,800 --> 00:08:46,900
[SPIT AND SPARKS CHUCKLING]

75
00:09:09,500 --> 00:09:11,700
Maps.

76
00:09:30,900 --> 00:09:35,300
MISTY: It was more than being orphans
that tied us together.

77
00:09:35,500 --> 00:09:38,300
Or even our friendship.

78
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:41,300
It was like destiny.

79
00:09:41,500 --> 00:09:42,800
MAPS:
Cross swords.

80
00:09:43,000 --> 00:09:44,000
[BO YS LAUGH]

81
00:09:44,200 --> 00:09:46,500
MISTY: We were even given
the same birth month.

82
00:09:46,700 --> 00:09:52,000
ALL: All for one, and one for all.
December boys.

83
00:10:00,300 --> 00:10:03,400
MISTY: The further we traveled
from what we knew...

84
00:10:03,600 --> 00:10:08,400
...the more it seemed like we were
being pulled into another world...

85
00:10:08,600 --> 00:10:11,300
...a world where all the doors
were open...

86
00:10:11,500 --> 00:10:14,900
...and anything was possible.

87
00:10:23,900 --> 00:10:26,400
[CHILDREN LAUGHING AND YELLING]

88
00:10:36,500 --> 00:10:39,200
RINGMASTER:
Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls...

89
00:10:39,700 --> 00:10:42,200
[RINGMASTER SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY]

90
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:49,400
The most bone-rattling,
jaw-clenching...

91
00:10:49,500 --> 00:10:52,800
...death-defying act
you've ever seen!

92
00:10:52,900 --> 00:10:58,100
The Wall of Death!

93
00:10:58,400 --> 00:11:00,900
[AUDIENCE CHEERING
AND APPLAUDING]

94
00:11:01,800 --> 00:11:06,000
The one, the only,
the bravest man on two wheels...

95
00:11:06,300 --> 00:11:07,900
...Fearless Forte!

96
00:11:26,000 --> 00:11:28,700
[THUNDER RUMBLING
IN THE DISTANCE]

97
00:11:43,700 --> 00:11:46,300
- You all right there, boys?
MAPS: Yes, Father.

98
00:11:46,500 --> 00:11:49,200
- Come along.
MAPS: Come on, fellows.

99
00:11:49,500 --> 00:11:52,100
Right you are.
Welcome aboard.

100
00:11:52,200 --> 00:11:55,200
Boys, this is Petty Officer
Bandy McAnsh.

101
00:11:55,400 --> 00:11:57,500
Father.

102
00:11:57,600 --> 00:11:59,900
MISTY:
Petty officer.

103
00:12:00,100 --> 00:12:01,700
BAND Y:
Oh. Ha.

104
00:12:01,900 --> 00:12:05,800
As you can see,
all present and accounted for.

105
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:08,500
Boys, I'd like you
to meet my lovely wife...

106
00:12:08,700 --> 00:12:12,200
...and the skipper
of this establishment, Mrs. McAnsh.

107
00:12:12,300 --> 00:12:13,400
Nice to meet you.

108
00:12:13,600 --> 00:12:17,500
MRS. McANSH: Father, we thank God
for your safe arrival.

109
00:12:17,800 --> 00:12:20,000
May his grace light your paths...

110
00:12:20,700 --> 00:12:25,600
...and give you the appropriate wisdom
and joy from your new experience.

111
00:12:25,700 --> 00:12:26,800
ALL:
Amen.

112
00:12:26,900 --> 00:12:28,400
[WHISPERS]
I knew there'd be a catch.

113
00:12:28,500 --> 00:12:31,000
Petty officer, show the new recruits
to their quarters...

114
00:12:31,100 --> 00:12:33,600
...and I'll finish in the galley.
- Ha-ha.

115
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:36,300
Well, have fun, boys.

116
00:12:36,500 --> 00:12:37,600
Thank you, Father.

117
00:12:37,800 --> 00:12:38,800
BAND Y:
Right.

118
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:40,900
Step this way.

119
00:12:41,100 --> 00:12:43,600
Welcome aboard.

120
00:12:44,100 --> 00:12:45,800
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

121
00:12:46,000 --> 00:12:48,500
[BAND Y BLOWS WHISTLE]

122
00:12:51,100 --> 00:12:52,500
[BAND Y CHUCKLES]

123
00:12:55,000 --> 00:12:57,500
[BAND Y PLAYING HARMONICA]

124
00:13:05,100 --> 00:13:06,600
[BAND Y CHUCKLES]

125
00:13:08,700 --> 00:13:11,600
BAND Y:
All right, mateys.

126
00:13:12,100 --> 00:13:14,400
It's been a long day.

127
00:13:14,600 --> 00:13:18,000
Time to settle down.
Everyone in bed.

128
00:13:19,600 --> 00:13:25,100
And we'll let the Old Specific
sing you a lullaby.

129
00:13:27,700 --> 00:13:29,400
Good night, boys.

130
00:13:39,800 --> 00:13:42,300
[WAVES CRASHING]

131
00:13:42,600 --> 00:13:43,900
MISTY:
The ocean's loud.

132
00:13:45,300 --> 00:13:48,700
- I didn't think it'd be this loud.
MAPS: Yeah.

133
00:13:48,900 --> 00:13:50,500
The Old Specific.

134
00:13:50,700 --> 00:13:53,800
SPARKS [WHISPERS]:
Hey, Spit, have a look at this.

135
00:14:02,500 --> 00:14:04,500
SPARKS:
Hey, what's that?

136
00:14:04,700 --> 00:14:07,300
I suppose you know
you'll be going to hell?

137
00:14:07,700 --> 00:14:09,600
Really?

138
00:14:11,000 --> 00:14:12,300
Now I'll have company.

139
00:14:12,400 --> 00:14:14,500
[SPIT AND SPARKS LAUGH]

140
00:14:15,500 --> 00:14:17,500
Knock it off, both of you.

141
00:14:17,700 --> 00:14:20,000
I'm trying to relax.

142
00:14:21,400 --> 00:14:22,700
[WOOD CREAKING]

143
00:14:22,900 --> 00:14:24,500
You hear that?

144
00:14:25,300 --> 00:14:27,600
SPARKS:
Is he coming?

145
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:32,200
SPIT [WHISPERS]:
Listen.

146
00:14:34,500 --> 00:14:36,200
[SPIT FARTS]

147
00:14:36,700 --> 00:14:38,500
My ass is snoring.

148
00:14:38,700 --> 00:14:40,700
[SPIT AND SPARKS LAUGH]

149
00:14:47,200 --> 00:14:49,700
[THUNDER CRASHING]

150
00:15:04,900 --> 00:15:07,300
MAPS:
Come on, mate.

151
00:15:35,400 --> 00:15:37,800
SPIT:
Last one in's a rotten egg!

152
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:40,800
SPARKS: Really? Looks like
you're the rotten egg, Spit.

153
00:15:40,900 --> 00:15:43,200
MAPS:
Come on, Mist.

154
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:47,100
SPARKS:
Come on, Misty.

155
00:15:47,200 --> 00:15:48,900
SPIT: Come on.
SPARKS: Come in.

156
00:15:51,300 --> 00:15:53,900
[BO YS LAUGHING AND CHATTERING]

157
00:15:54,100 --> 00:15:56,000
SPARKS:
Have a look at this.

158
00:15:56,200 --> 00:15:57,400
SPIT:
Spark, come on.

159
00:15:57,600 --> 00:15:59,800
SPARKS:
Yeah, coming.

160
00:16:02,600 --> 00:16:04,900
SPIT:
Hey!

161
00:16:05,000 --> 00:16:06,200
Hey!

162
00:16:06,400 --> 00:16:08,100
- Hey, fishing boat.
MAPS: Hello?

163
00:16:09,000 --> 00:16:10,300
- Hey.
SPIT: Over here.

164
00:16:10,500 --> 00:16:11,600
MISTY:
Hey, over here.

165
00:16:11,800 --> 00:16:13,900
Look.

166
00:16:16,400 --> 00:16:20,200
MISTY:
Come on. Race you to the rocks.

167
00:17:10,000 --> 00:17:11,400
Ah!

168
00:17:11,600 --> 00:17:14,000
Ooh! Ahh!

169
00:17:15,800 --> 00:17:18,100
MAPS:
Hey, fellows.

170
00:17:27,600 --> 00:17:30,400
Somebody's set themselves up.

171
00:17:34,100 --> 00:17:35,700
Whoa!

172
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,600
Check out the cordial.

173
00:17:40,900 --> 00:17:42,400
- Maps.
- They're somebody else's.

174
00:17:42,600 --> 00:17:44,700
Don't take any.

175
00:18:04,700 --> 00:18:06,100
Hey.

176
00:18:06,200 --> 00:18:07,900
Who wants a ride?

177
00:18:15,600 --> 00:18:17,500
[BO YS HOLLERING]

178
00:18:31,000 --> 00:18:33,200
[HORSE NEIGHS]

179
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:49,800
MAPS: Whoo!
MISTY: Coming back down.

180
00:18:56,500 --> 00:18:57,800
SPIT:
Hey, guys.

181
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:00,000
MISTY:
What is it?

182
00:19:00,800 --> 00:19:02,600
Find out.

183
00:19:38,600 --> 00:19:41,600
MISTY: She was the most beautiful
woman I'd ever seen...

184
00:19:41,800 --> 00:19:43,700
...other than Our Lady.

185
00:19:43,900 --> 00:19:46,600
Sleek as a seal.

186
00:19:46,800 --> 00:19:50,400
Mind you, I hadn't seen
nearly as much of Our Lady.

187
00:19:50,600 --> 00:19:52,100
[SPARKS GRO ANS]

188
00:19:52,700 --> 00:19:56,300
Sparks. Come on. Sparks, get up.

189
00:19:56,700 --> 00:19:59,400
MAPS:
Come on. Get up.

190
00:20:07,200 --> 00:20:10,100
WOMAN:
We heard you were coming.

191
00:20:16,200 --> 00:20:18,700
I'm Teresa.

192
00:20:20,100 --> 00:20:24,000
MISTY: This was as close as I'd come
to a religious epiphany.

193
00:20:24,300 --> 00:20:27,400
But whatever ideas I had
about becoming a priest...

194
00:20:27,600 --> 00:20:29,400
...quickly climbed into the back seat.

195
00:20:31,800 --> 00:20:33,700
TERESA:
How did you get these names?

196
00:20:33,900 --> 00:20:36,800
We call him Spark
because he stuck a knife in a toaster...

197
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:40,000
...and nearly set the orphanage
on fire.

198
00:20:43,900 --> 00:20:46,000
And you? You are Spit?

199
00:20:46,200 --> 00:20:48,000
[SPIT HAWKS]

200
00:20:49,900 --> 00:20:53,900
SPIT: My dad flew a Spitfire during
the war. And I'm a champion spitter.

201
00:20:54,500 --> 00:20:57,000
- And you, you like maps.
SPIT: No.

202
00:20:57,300 --> 00:20:59,900
He's got a birthmark on his chest
shaped like Tasmania.

203
00:21:00,100 --> 00:21:02,400
I'm all right.

204
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:09,300
If he doesn't want any,
I'll have seconds.

205
00:21:16,600 --> 00:21:18,500
And why are you Misty?

206
00:21:18,700 --> 00:21:20,300
SPIT:
Because he's a waterworks.

207
00:21:23,200 --> 00:21:26,500
TERESA:
Okay. I'm going now.

208
00:21:26,700 --> 00:21:29,700
Fearless is home tonight.

209
00:21:42,400 --> 00:21:43,700
Who's that?

210
00:21:43,900 --> 00:21:47,900
That's Shellback.
He fishes for Henry.

211
00:21:48,500 --> 00:21:51,900
Is Henry a person or a fish?

212
00:22:36,500 --> 00:22:38,900
MRS. McANSH:
O, my good angel...

213
00:22:39,100 --> 00:22:40,400
[MOTORC YCLE APPRO ACHING]

214
00:22:40,600 --> 00:22:43,200
...whom God has appointed
my guardian...

215
00:22:43,400 --> 00:22:45,900
...watch over me during this night...

216
00:22:46,100 --> 00:22:47,500
...and protect me...

217
00:22:48,300 --> 00:22:51,500
...from evil in my thoughts
as well as my deeds.

218
00:22:54,200 --> 00:22:56,800
In the deepest hour of darkness...

219
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:00,000
...let your presence lead the way...

220
00:23:00,200 --> 00:23:02,800
...to righteousness...

221
00:23:03,000 --> 00:23:05,400
...and goodness.

222
00:23:07,800 --> 00:23:09,500
[MOTORC YCLE HORN HONKING]

223
00:23:15,200 --> 00:23:16,800
Boys.

224
00:23:17,100 --> 00:23:20,800
God cares nothing for motorcycles.

225
00:23:39,400 --> 00:23:41,900
SHELLBACK:
Henry.

226
00:23:43,700 --> 00:23:45,400
[IMITATING MOTORC YCLE]

227
00:23:46,200 --> 00:23:50,700
MISTY: You're gonna get us in trouble.
- I know how to ride one of these.

228
00:23:51,100 --> 00:23:53,200
My dad had one, only bigger.

229
00:23:53,400 --> 00:23:55,700
SPARKS: Bullshit, your dad died
when you was 3.

230
00:23:55,900 --> 00:23:57,100
Get down.

231
00:23:57,300 --> 00:23:58,400
FEARLESS:
Hey.

232
00:23:58,500 --> 00:24:00,800
Somebody say
you could climb up there?

233
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:04,100
SPIT:
We was just looking.

234
00:24:04,800 --> 00:24:06,900
That what you call it?

235
00:24:07,300 --> 00:24:09,300
SPIT:
We're here on holiday.

236
00:24:09,500 --> 00:24:12,700
My dad had a bike just like this.

237
00:24:12,900 --> 00:24:14,100
FEARLESS:
That so?

238
00:24:14,300 --> 00:24:17,100
I saw you on the Wall of Death.

239
00:24:17,600 --> 00:24:20,000
I saw you go through the fire
and everything.

240
00:24:20,200 --> 00:24:22,700
You must be about
the best cyclist there is.

241
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:25,700
[MOTORC YCLE REVVING]

242
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:30,600
- You boys like a thrill, do you?
- Yeah.

243
00:24:32,500 --> 00:24:34,100
Who's first?

244
00:24:37,300 --> 00:24:39,300
I've been on a bike before.

245
00:24:39,500 --> 00:24:41,200
I'll go.

246
00:24:59,900 --> 00:25:01,800
[HORN HONKING]

247
00:25:25,800 --> 00:25:28,200
Faster. Faster.

248
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:35,600
[LAUGHING]

249
00:25:37,500 --> 00:25:39,100
Whoo!

250
00:25:47,400 --> 00:25:48,500
Yes!

251
00:25:52,200 --> 00:25:54,500
[BO YS HOLLERING]

252
00:26:24,400 --> 00:26:26,500
[GENERATOR STARTING UP]

253
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:41,900
[FEARLESS LAUGHING]

254
00:26:42,100 --> 00:26:45,100
SPIT: At least someone's
having a good time.

255
00:27:07,700 --> 00:27:08,700
How you going?

256
00:27:11,400 --> 00:27:13,500
WATSON:
Good night.

257
00:27:14,000 --> 00:27:16,300
See you later.

258
00:27:21,600 --> 00:27:22,700
"How you going?"

259
00:27:22,900 --> 00:27:26,100
You'll be up her
like a rat up a drainpipe.

260
00:27:27,700 --> 00:27:30,000
SPIT:
Come on, give us a go.

261
00:27:30,600 --> 00:27:32,100
Why do we have to be stuck here?

262
00:27:32,300 --> 00:27:35,500
SPIT: That's easy.
SPARKS: No, it's not.

263
00:27:36,200 --> 00:27:38,700
I'm not stuck.

264
00:27:48,200 --> 00:27:50,200
MAPS [WHISPERING]:
Go.

265
00:27:50,500 --> 00:27:52,300
Go.

266
00:27:56,200 --> 00:27:58,800
WATSON: The least you can do
is three cheers for the corpse.

267
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:00,800
Hip, hip, hurray!

268
00:28:01,000 --> 00:28:02,500
LUC Y:
Boys.

269
00:28:02,600 --> 00:28:03,700
Thanks, Luce.

270
00:28:03,800 --> 00:28:05,700
FEARLESS: Yeah, thanks.
SCULLY: Thank you, Lucy.

271
00:28:05,800 --> 00:28:08,900
WATSON: That is the same sort of thing
that happened to Archbishop O'Donnell.

272
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:11,100
I was there in the church
Sunday morning...

273
00:28:11,200 --> 00:28:13,500
...come to the end of the sermon,
and he says:

274
00:28:13,700 --> 00:28:17,900
"Therefore, many are cold
but few are frozen."

275
00:28:18,100 --> 00:28:19,400
And it was the middle of winter.

276
00:28:19,600 --> 00:28:21,100
[MEN LAUGHING]

277
00:28:21,600 --> 00:28:24,000
FEARLESS: You know, it's good
with Lucy around this summer.

278
00:28:24,200 --> 00:28:28,900
- Give Tess some girl company.
- By the way, how's her father doing?

279
00:28:29,100 --> 00:28:32,200
Still looking for work in Darwin.

280
00:28:32,400 --> 00:28:33,700
Five minutes to dinner.

281
00:28:34,200 --> 00:28:36,900
FEARLESS: Thanks, darling.
WATSON: Cheers, Teresa.

282
00:28:37,600 --> 00:28:40,800
Hey, he just swiped your beer.

283
00:28:42,500 --> 00:28:44,500
FEARLESS:
Let them have their fun.

284
00:28:45,300 --> 00:28:47,200
SPIT:
Wait for me. Wait.

285
00:28:47,400 --> 00:28:49,600
I don't expect it's a picnic
where they're from.

286
00:28:49,900 --> 00:28:52,800
SCULLY: For all you hear,
it's not too bad out there.

287
00:28:53,000 --> 00:28:55,100
They're well cared for.

288
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:57,500
Yeah, I'll bet they are.

289
00:28:57,700 --> 00:29:01,100
I think I'll go and see
if I can give the girls a hand.

290
00:29:01,700 --> 00:29:04,800
FEARLESS:
Still, it's not the same as a family.

291
00:29:05,000 --> 00:29:06,100
SCULLY:
Indeed, it isn't.

292
00:29:07,400 --> 00:29:10,900
I think Tess blames me
for taking her away from her family.

293
00:29:11,100 --> 00:29:12,900
Her country.

294
00:29:13,400 --> 00:29:16,200
We're supposed to be
starting our own out here.

295
00:29:18,100 --> 00:29:21,300
You know, maybe it's the accident
that shook something loose.

296
00:29:21,500 --> 00:29:25,100
Well, there's no substitute for family,
that's for sure.

297
00:29:25,300 --> 00:29:27,200
You're not saying
you're giving up hope?

298
00:29:27,400 --> 00:29:28,600
No.

299
00:29:29,300 --> 00:29:31,400
I'm not saying that.

300
00:29:31,600 --> 00:29:33,500
It's just...

301
00:29:33,700 --> 00:29:35,800
...you get to a point, you know?

302
00:29:35,900 --> 00:29:38,800
You start to see things
like they are.

303
00:29:40,300 --> 00:29:42,900
Sure never pictured
a life without kids.

304
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:48,800
SCULLY: The pity of it is,
there are children...

305
00:29:49,000 --> 00:29:53,900
...just like those boys next door,
desperate for a good home.

306
00:29:54,400 --> 00:29:58,800
And here you are,
desperate for children.

307
00:30:02,500 --> 00:30:03,800
FEARLESS:
Mm.

308
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:06,400
You got a point there, Father.

309
00:30:06,600 --> 00:30:08,200
We want a kid...

310
00:30:09,100 --> 00:30:11,700
...and they need parents.

311
00:30:11,900 --> 00:30:15,800
We could just line them up
and pick which one we like the best.

312
00:30:34,900 --> 00:30:36,300
They get you?

313
00:30:36,400 --> 00:30:38,000
What happened?

314
00:30:38,200 --> 00:30:40,600
My glasses got knocked off.

315
00:30:40,800 --> 00:30:43,300
MAPS:
We saved you some.

316
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:48,400
I'm going to bed.

317
00:30:56,300 --> 00:30:58,000
SPARKS:
Come on, Spit.

318
00:31:17,700 --> 00:31:19,800
[MOTORC YCLE STARTS]

319
00:31:41,600 --> 00:31:43,500
Dad.

320
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:50,300
MRS. McANSH:
Thank you, Vernon.

321
00:31:51,700 --> 00:31:53,400
More tea?

322
00:31:53,700 --> 00:31:56,000
Oh. There you are.

323
00:31:56,200 --> 00:31:59,300
I want you all to take notice...

324
00:31:59,500 --> 00:32:02,800
...of how sharp young Vernon
looks this morning.

325
00:32:05,700 --> 00:32:08,200
Good on you, son.

326
00:32:15,800 --> 00:32:17,100
[MISTY GRUNTS]

327
00:32:17,300 --> 00:32:19,400
You all right?

328
00:32:25,300 --> 00:32:28,300
If it's all right,
I'd like to say grace.

329
00:32:29,700 --> 00:32:31,600
That'd be lovely, Vernon.

330
00:32:31,800 --> 00:32:35,800
O Lord, we beseech thee
in your wondrous grace...

331
00:32:35,800 --> 00:32:40,400
...and thank you for the food
we're about to receive. Amen.

332
00:32:40,600 --> 00:32:42,900
ALL:
Amen.

333
00:32:46,000 --> 00:32:48,300
SPIT:
Ha-ha! Got you.

334
00:32:49,300 --> 00:32:50,600
SPARKS:
Hey, get back.

335
00:32:50,800 --> 00:32:53,700
No. Don't leave me here. No.

336
00:32:53,800 --> 00:32:56,000
- No fair.
SPIT: Yeah.

337
00:32:56,200 --> 00:32:58,000
SPARKS: I got you already.
SPIT: You didn't.

338
00:32:58,100 --> 00:33:00,600
SPARKS: You're it.
SPIT: No.

339
00:33:00,800 --> 00:33:03,800
SPARKS:
If you get me, I'll kiss Sister Beatrice.

340
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:05,900
[SPARKS AND SPIT LAUGHING]

341
00:33:06,500 --> 00:33:09,500
Hey, you can't run around
the cross.

342
00:33:34,100 --> 00:33:36,200
EDNA:
Where is my precious Misty?

343
00:33:36,400 --> 00:33:38,100
He's been adopted.

344
00:33:39,200 --> 00:33:42,100
He was always the best of the lot.

345
00:34:17,600 --> 00:34:19,900
MAPS:
You the one living in the cave?

346
00:34:20,100 --> 00:34:23,600
I don't live there.
I just come up here to observe.

347
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:28,600
You can come up if you want.

348
00:34:35,600 --> 00:34:37,600
You one of them orphan kids?

349
00:34:37,900 --> 00:34:39,700
Yeah.

350
00:34:40,800 --> 00:34:43,600
- What's your name?
- Maps.

351
00:34:43,700 --> 00:34:46,600
So, what are you observing?

352
00:34:46,700 --> 00:34:49,100
You had a good look at these rocks?

353
00:34:49,200 --> 00:34:50,800
I've seen them.

354
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:53,400
Haven't you noticed
anything strange?

355
00:34:53,600 --> 00:34:56,400
They are weird-looking.

356
00:34:57,800 --> 00:35:00,500
They were left here by aliens.

357
00:35:00,800 --> 00:35:04,900
Same as Stonehenge.
You ever heard of Stonehenge?

358
00:35:05,100 --> 00:35:06,200
Kind of.

359
00:35:06,400 --> 00:35:08,100
Well, it's the same.

360
00:35:08,300 --> 00:35:11,500
When they come back,
I'll be ready.

361
00:35:11,700 --> 00:35:13,400
MAPS:
People from outer space?

362
00:35:13,500 --> 00:35:15,800
LUC Y:
Of course.

363
00:35:26,600 --> 00:35:28,900
I don't guess you see
many women where you're from.

364
00:35:29,100 --> 00:35:33,600
Nuns, mostly. Nuns.

365
00:35:34,000 --> 00:35:36,500
Yeah, I've seen some of those.

366
00:35:38,100 --> 00:35:40,800
Want some? It's my last one.

367
00:36:17,300 --> 00:36:19,200
By the way...

368
00:36:19,400 --> 00:36:21,600
...my name is Lucy.

369
00:36:21,800 --> 00:36:24,000
Good to meet you.

370
00:36:33,800 --> 00:36:36,800
SPARKS: Hey, look, what's that?
SPIT: Yeah?

371
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:38,800
SPARKS:
Come on, Spit.

372
00:36:38,900 --> 00:36:41,000
SPIT: Hey, wait up.
- No.

373
00:36:41,200 --> 00:36:42,200
SPIT:
Dirty trickster.

374
00:36:50,300 --> 00:36:52,500
SPARKS:
Look at all this.

375
00:36:57,100 --> 00:36:59,400
SPIT:
Oh, check out the net.

376
00:36:59,500 --> 00:37:03,900
And this is a spear.
What do you reckon he does with this?

377
00:37:08,500 --> 00:37:11,300
SHELLBACK:
What the hell do you think you're doing?

378
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:17,600
Uh, we...

379
00:37:17,700 --> 00:37:20,000
We was just looking around.

380
00:37:21,900 --> 00:37:25,500
Seeing as you can see so well,
can you read that sign?

381
00:37:27,800 --> 00:37:31,500
That's a heavy line you got there.
What are you fishing for, Moby Dick?

382
00:37:31,700 --> 00:37:35,800
When it rains, Spark's the best
fisherman at Bible Creek.

383
00:37:37,100 --> 00:37:39,100
You see a creek around here, boy-o?

384
00:37:39,300 --> 00:37:42,800
He's worried I'll catch Henry
before he does.

385
00:37:44,700 --> 00:37:47,300
What do you know about Henry?

386
00:37:47,700 --> 00:37:50,300
A fish is a fish.

387
00:37:52,200 --> 00:37:56,300
Henry's a king of fishes.
He's a masterpiece.

388
00:37:56,500 --> 00:38:00,000
He was swimming in these waters
long before you were born.

389
00:38:00,200 --> 00:38:03,700
He's bigger and smarter
than you will ever be.

390
00:38:04,000 --> 00:38:06,200
Get lost.

391
00:38:15,100 --> 00:38:18,800
FEARLESS: Can't I make a suggestion
without getting my bloody head bit off?

392
00:38:18,900 --> 00:38:21,900
It's not a suggestion.
You gave up.

393
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:25,100
For chrissake, Tess.
Listen to me.

394
00:38:25,300 --> 00:38:27,900
All right? I'm not saying
that we won't have a baby.

395
00:38:28,000 --> 00:38:30,000
All I'm saying
is we should talk about...

396
00:38:30,100 --> 00:38:33,100
...adopting one of those kids
that needs a home.

397
00:38:37,400 --> 00:38:40,000
I talked to someone
at the archdiocese.

398
00:38:40,200 --> 00:38:41,900
It's possible.

399
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:44,100
That's all I'm saying.

400
00:38:46,300 --> 00:38:49,700
So you've decided.

401
00:38:49,900 --> 00:38:51,600
FEARLESS:
No.

402
00:38:51,800 --> 00:38:53,300
[TERESA SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

403
00:38:53,400 --> 00:38:55,400
FEARLESS:
Tess... No...

404
00:38:55,600 --> 00:38:57,100
Tess, you're not listening to me.

405
00:38:57,300 --> 00:39:01,600
No. It's your fault
I can't have babies.

406
00:39:07,500 --> 00:39:09,600
[BO YS HOLLERING]

407
00:39:14,400 --> 00:39:16,800
Whoa, look at that.

408
00:39:16,900 --> 00:39:19,600
- Come on, put some more on.
MAPS: You don't need any more.

409
00:39:19,800 --> 00:39:22,800
She's getting naked.

410
00:39:23,700 --> 00:39:27,100
MAPS [WHISPERING]:
No. Guys, wait. Wait. Go slow.

411
00:40:03,000 --> 00:40:04,800
[SPARKS GRO ANS]

412
00:40:15,800 --> 00:40:17,800
[CLANGS]

413
00:40:23,500 --> 00:40:25,800
MAPS:
Quick, run.

414
00:40:29,700 --> 00:40:31,600
[DOORKNOB RATTLING]

415
00:40:32,300 --> 00:40:34,300
I'll yell.

416
00:40:35,100 --> 00:40:38,300
Misty, I know there's gotta be
a very good explanation for that...

417
00:40:38,500 --> 00:40:40,500
...so why don't you come out
and tell us what it is?

418
00:40:40,700 --> 00:40:43,000
I promise nothing
will happen to you.

419
00:40:45,500 --> 00:40:46,900
No.

420
00:40:47,900 --> 00:40:50,200
Just remember,
I keep you from getting killed...

421
00:40:50,400 --> 00:40:52,600
...and soon we'll all be back
at St. Greg's.

422
00:40:52,800 --> 00:40:55,300
[WHISPERS]
That's what you think.

423
00:41:10,900 --> 00:41:13,100
[SHOWER RUNNING]

424
00:41:18,900 --> 00:41:21,600
[MRS. McANSH SINGING
"SILENT NIGHT"]

425
00:42:29,300 --> 00:42:31,000
MRS. McANSH:
Boys...

426
00:42:31,200 --> 00:42:33,400
...I have great news.

427
00:42:35,400 --> 00:42:38,400
Father Scully
is taking confession today.

428
00:42:38,600 --> 00:42:42,300
Clean slate.
Just in time for Christmas, eh?

429
00:42:42,500 --> 00:42:43,800
- Great.
MISTY: Beauty.

430
00:42:43,900 --> 00:42:47,600
- Ripper.
SPIT: Yeah, great.

431
00:42:50,300 --> 00:42:52,100
SCULLY:
Next.

432
00:42:53,300 --> 00:42:55,400
Vernon.

433
00:43:02,500 --> 00:43:04,100
What's troubling you, son?

434
00:43:04,300 --> 00:43:06,900
MISTY:
Bless me, Father, for I have sinned.

435
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:09,000
SCULLY: How long is it
since your last confession?

436
00:43:09,200 --> 00:43:12,000
About three weeks.

437
00:43:13,200 --> 00:43:15,700
I've had some unclean thoughts.

438
00:43:16,400 --> 00:43:19,200
And I pulled a face
at one of the sisters.

439
00:43:19,900 --> 00:43:21,200
Is that all?

440
00:43:21,300 --> 00:43:23,200
Not exactly.

441
00:43:24,800 --> 00:43:29,000
Oh, come on, lad.
I'm gonna need basting in a minute.

442
00:43:30,900 --> 00:43:34,000
Let's say there was something
you wanted.

443
00:43:35,400 --> 00:43:38,900
You know, something you wanted
more than anything.

444
00:43:41,100 --> 00:43:43,200
And you had an advantage...

445
00:43:43,600 --> 00:43:46,400
...because the others don't know.

446
00:43:47,300 --> 00:43:50,300
What is the point in giving it up?

447
00:43:50,400 --> 00:43:52,400
I mean...

448
00:43:52,600 --> 00:43:55,900
Look, I can't guess, son.
You're gonna have to tell me.

449
00:43:57,000 --> 00:44:01,500
It'll ease your mind
if you unburden yourself.

450
00:44:01,600 --> 00:44:04,100
I heard something.

451
00:44:04,500 --> 00:44:06,800
Can you tell what he's saying?

452
00:44:07,400 --> 00:44:09,800
Something about...

453
00:44:10,100 --> 00:44:12,500
...big breasts.
SPIT: Ha-ha.

454
00:44:12,700 --> 00:44:14,600
What?

455
00:44:14,800 --> 00:44:17,300
SCULLY:
If you keep this knowledge to yourself...

456
00:44:17,500 --> 00:44:19,800
...are you being fair
with the other boys?

457
00:44:20,400 --> 00:44:23,300
I think you should tell them.

458
00:44:23,500 --> 00:44:28,000
The burdens and the joys of this world
are always better shared.

459
00:44:28,200 --> 00:44:29,600
Do you understand me?

460
00:44:30,200 --> 00:44:31,800
I've got to share.

461
00:44:32,000 --> 00:44:33,200
SCULLY:
That's right.

462
00:44:33,700 --> 00:44:36,500
Now, for your penance,
you say five Hail Marys...

463
00:44:36,600 --> 00:44:38,300
Something else happened last night.

464
00:44:39,000 --> 00:44:41,900
Save it till next time. I'm cooked.

465
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:48,600
Oh, Hail Mary. Oh, Hail Mary.

466
00:45:03,500 --> 00:45:05,400
It's time to come clean.

467
00:45:05,600 --> 00:45:07,400
Get off me.
My arm can't breathe.

468
00:45:07,600 --> 00:45:10,200
Tell us or we'll slag you.

469
00:45:12,000 --> 00:45:14,100
MAPS: Now then,
I wouldn't want anything...

470
00:45:14,300 --> 00:45:18,100
...coming out of Spit's mouth
landing on my face.

471
00:45:23,600 --> 00:45:24,600
I'll tell you.

472
00:45:27,100 --> 00:45:30,600
Fearless and Teresa
are gonna adopt one of us.

473
00:45:31,600 --> 00:45:33,100
I swear.

474
00:45:34,300 --> 00:45:36,300
Let him up.

475
00:45:39,600 --> 00:45:41,800
- I swear.
- When?

476
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:43,800
I don't know.

477
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:47,900
Before we leave. They're gonna choose
which one of us they like best.

478
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:50,000
Why would they want us?
We're too old.

479
00:45:50,100 --> 00:45:51,700
Speak for yourself.

480
00:45:51,900 --> 00:45:54,300
We're not as old as you are.

481
00:46:00,100 --> 00:46:02,600
SPARKS:
Did they say who they want?

482
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:07,900
You don't know which it is.

483
00:46:15,700 --> 00:46:19,200
MRS. McANSH: Where are the others?
- I'm not sure.

484
00:46:47,400 --> 00:46:50,000
My real name's Vernon.

485
00:46:52,100 --> 00:46:56,000
You know,
Africa is just over there.

486
00:47:07,200 --> 00:47:10,100
Vernon, do you remember
your parents?

487
00:47:11,200 --> 00:47:13,600
I think I do...

488
00:47:14,100 --> 00:47:17,400
...but maybe it was a photo.

489
00:47:18,700 --> 00:47:22,800
My dad was tall and tan.

490
00:47:23,000 --> 00:47:27,100
And my mother
had long, dark hair.

491
00:47:27,600 --> 00:47:30,100
She was smiling.

492
00:47:31,600 --> 00:47:34,500
They died in a car accident.

493
00:47:35,100 --> 00:47:39,900
I don't know why I wasn't there.
Nobody ever told me.

494
00:47:41,800 --> 00:47:47,000
If my parents were still alive,
I'd never let them out of my sight.

495
00:47:47,600 --> 00:47:49,300
[HORSE NEIGHS]

496
00:47:51,700 --> 00:47:53,800
MISTY:
What's he doing?

497
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:55,800
That's Socrates.

498
00:47:56,000 --> 00:48:00,400
Shellback says he catches fish
and feeds them to the cats.

499
00:48:00,600 --> 00:48:02,200
Have you seen him do it?

500
00:48:02,300 --> 00:48:07,400
No, but I believe
a lot of things I can't see.

501
00:48:08,300 --> 00:48:10,400
Me too.

502
00:48:28,800 --> 00:48:31,500
You ever think about
running away?

503
00:48:32,300 --> 00:48:34,100
There's no place to run.

504
00:48:34,200 --> 00:48:37,700
When I get 18,
they make you leave anyway.

505
00:48:45,200 --> 00:48:46,200
Like music?

506
00:48:46,500 --> 00:48:51,500
[CREEDENCE CLEARWATER REVIVAL'S
"WHO'LL STOP THE RAIN" PLAYING]

